{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516680"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:45:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:45:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12686"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12686"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.08,0.02,0.58,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5154"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106773"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5154"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12686"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89253"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1153"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1311"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8706"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8936"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8964"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42799"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44000"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106773"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents with a six-week history of intermittent headaches and blurred vision, which were more frequent during periods of physical exertion or when she wakes in the morning. She has also experienced nausea, and vomiting. Her history is significant for polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), which she manages with oral contraceptive pills.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 142/86 mmHg, pulse 82/min, temperature 37.4\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 16/min and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 98% on room air. Her BMI is 33. Fundoscopy shows papilloedema and there is an enlarged blind spot on visual field testing. When asked to look to the left, she reports horizontal diplopia and this is associated with failure to abduct on leftward gaze. She also has stiffness in her neck but no signs of meningeal irritation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Meningioma","Prolactinoma","Postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome (POTS)","Idiopathic intracranial hypertension","Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s symptoms are consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eidiopathic intracranial hypertension,\u003C/strong\u003E also known as pseudotumour cerebri. Idiopathic intracranial hypertension is a condition in which the pressure within the skull rises without an actual mass lesion. The diagnosis is made based on the clinical presentation, elevated CSF pressure obtained during lumbar puncture, and imaging studies excluding a structural cause. Imaging needs to be a plain and contrast study (preferably a MRI) to exclude venous thrombosis and meningioma. Papilloedema suggests elevated intracranial pressure. Furthermore, the patient demonstrates evidence of a left abducens nerve palsy, which is a false localising sign that may occur in 10% of patients due to increased intracranial pressures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emeningioma\u003C/strong\u003E is a possible differential diagnosis, but it typically presents with gradually worsening symptoms and is more common in older patients. However it is twice as common in women and can be a prolonged history, so imaging is need to exclude meningioma. The most common locations of meningiomas are the convexities of the brain and the parasagittal region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eprolactinoma\u003C/strong\u003E may present with endocrine abnormalities like galactorrhoea and amenorrhoea. It may also cause bitemporal hemianopia if it compromises the optic chiasm, but would not typically cause blurred vision, enhanced blind spot, or papilloedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPostural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome (POTS) \u003C/strong\u003Eis a condition characterised by an abnormal increase in heart rate upon standing, along with other symptoms such as lightheadedness and fatigue. While some of the patient\u0027s symptoms, such as headaches and nausea, may be present in POTS, the presence of papilloedema and an enlarged blind spot on visual field testing make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebral venous sinus thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare but serious condition that can cause similar symptoms as IIH. It is more common in women, particularly during pregnancy and the postpartum period, as well as in patients with prothrombotic conditions and use of Oral contraceptives. The six week history makes this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Idiopathic intracranial hypertension (IIH) is a condition that results in increased intracranial pressure, leading to symptoms such as headache, nausea, vomiting, and visual disturbances.","Treatment options for IIH include weight loss, acetazolamide, and optic nerve sheath fenestration"],"references":["NORDIC Idiopathic Intracranial Hypertension Study Group Writing Committee; Wall M, McDermott MP, Kieburtz KD, Corbett JJ, Feldon SE, Friedman DI, Katz DM, Keltner JL, Schron EB, Kupersmith MJ. Effect of acetazolamide on visual function in patients with idiopathic intracranial hypertension and mild visual loss: the idiopathic intracranial hypertension treatment trial. JAMA. 2014 Apr 23-30;311(16):1641-51. doi: 10.1001/jama.2014.3312. PMID: 24756514; PMCID: PMC4362615. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24756514/","Wakerley BR, Mollan SP, Sinclair AJ. Idiopathic intracranial hypertension: Update on diagnosis and management. Clin Med (Lond). 2020 Jul;20(4):384-388. doi: 10.7861/clinmed.2020-0232. PMID: 32675143; PMCID: PMC7385768. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32675143/","Wang MTM, Bhatti MT, Danesh-Meyer HV. Idiopathic intracranial hypertension: Pathophysiology, diagnosis and management. J Clin Neurosci. 2022 Jan;95:172-179. doi: 10.1016/j.jocn.2021.11.029. Epub 2021 Dec 17. PMID: 34929642. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34929642/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89253"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12686"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89253"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-22T14:19:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-22T14:19:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5154"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106773"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta